      <section>
        <div class="assign-details-body">
          <p><span class="assign-text-lead">CONTEXT</span>
          You’ve already started to build your network by scheduling and having informational interviews to explore potential career paths. In securing an internship or job for the summer, networking is important in order to find out about new opportunities that you normally would not have known about or position yourself to apply for competitive opportunities. The more diverse your network is beyond your usual circle of family, friends, and colleagues, the better off you’ll be in finding new and different opportunities that continue to accelerate your growth, push your learning boundaries and motivate you to go Beyond Z.  So it’s important that you learn how to cultivate relationships with weak ties and to build up confidence talking to people you don’t know very well.
          </p>
          <p>
          Besides earning money, your relationships are another valuable resource, or a form of capital. In fact, researchers like Dr. Robert Putnam at Harvard University have coined the term, “social capital” which refers to “the social trust, norms, and networks that people can draw upon to solve common problems.” <a href="http://www.bettertogether.org/socialcapital.htm">(Source here).</a> It’s the reciprocal relationships that allow people to do things for each other and goes beyond feel-good emotions, but transfer actual benefits like information, cooperation, and support among members in the network. 
          </p>
        </div>
